hands_on_practices.problem:
In a fully ionized, unmagnetized, hydrogenic plasma with ion charge number $Z_{i}=1$, consider steady collisional electron transport driven by a uniform electric field $E$ along $x$. Let the electron distribution function be written as $f = f_{M} + \delta f$, where $f_{M}$ is the Maxwellian and $|\delta f| \ll f_{M}$. Linearizing the Fokker–Planck (FP) equation about $f_{M}$ and projecting onto the $l=1$ spherical harmonic (the component that carries the electric current), one obtains an inhomogeneous equation for the velocity-space function that can be solved by expanding in generalized Sonine polynomials $S_{n}^{(3/2)}(x)$, with $x$ a dimensionless squared speed. In a Galerkin formulation, the expansion coefficients $\{a_{n}\}$ satisfy a linear system
$$
\sum_{m=0}^{\infty} C_{nm}\, a_{m} \;=\; b_{n},
$$
where $C_{nm}$ are matrix elements of the linearized collision operator and $b_{n}$ are the forcing overlaps induced by the electric field. The component $a_{0}$ sets the amplitude of the lowest-order energy-weighted $l=1$ perturbation and is proportional to the electron conductivity; equivalently, the resistivity $\eta$ is proportional to $1/a_{0}$. The Spitzer resistivity is the value obtained when the infinite expansion is solved; truncating the Sonine expansion at the leading term approximates $a_{0}$ by $a_{0}^{(1)} = b_{0}/C_{00}$.

(a) Explain, from first principles of kinetic theory and asymptotic expansions, the limitations of using a truncated Sonine expansion for collisional transport, particularly when only the leading term is retained. Your explanation should reference the assumptions underlying near-Maxwellian closures, the role of higher-order velocity moments in representing energy dependence of the collision operator, and conditions under which the truncation can introduce non-negligible error in the Spitzer resistivity.

(b) To obtain a quantitative estimate of the truncation error in the Spitzer resistivity when only the leading term is retained, use a two-mode Galerkin model in which the Sonine expansion is truncated after $n=1$. Assume the following dimensionless, normalized collision matrix elements and forcing overlaps (appropriate to the Lorentz-gas limit and a hydrogenic plasma; they have been precomputed for a representative parameter point):
$$
C_{00} = 1,\quad C_{11} = 6,\quad C_{01} = C_{10} = 0.4,\quad b_{0} = 1,\quad b_{1} = 0.15.
$$
Solve the $2 \times 2$ system
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
C_{00}  C_{01} \\
C_{10}  C_{11}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
a_{0} \\
a_{1}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
b_{0} \\
b_{1}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
to obtain $a_{0}^{(2)}$. Let $\eta_{(1)} \propto 1/a_{0}^{(1)}$ and $\eta_{(2)} \propto 1/a_{0}^{(2)}$. Compute the relative error
$$
\varepsilon_{\eta} \;=\; \frac{\eta_{(1)} - \eta_{(2)}}{\eta_{(2)}}
$$
that results from retaining only the leading term. Round your final numerical result for $\varepsilon_{\eta}$ to four significant figures. The answer is dimensionless; report it as a decimal number.
